UID:feminist-gaming-fellowship-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260709T211504Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260712
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260713
SUMMARY:Deadline: Feminist Gaming Fellowship: Open Call 2026
DESCRIPTION:The Feminist Gaming Project is opening applications for its fir
 st Fellowship cohort: five fellows from different creative and research fi
 elds spending three months developing 3D assets\, tools\, and documentatio
 n for its Open Access Asset Library (OAL)\, a free\, open repository of in
 clusive 3D content created by\, with\, and for intersectionally feminist a
 nd diverse communities. Where mainstream marketplaces default to hyper-ath
 letic\, idealized\, or hyper-sexualized characters\, the OAL offers averag
 e bodies\, real postures\, everyday objects\, and the kinds of lives most 
 games leave out (pregnancy and postpartum\, care work\, ageing\, disabilit
 y\, domestic labor). This first cohort is dedicated to 3D content. Support
 ed by the Creative Industries Fund NL and working across the Netherlands\,
  Türkiye\, Germany\, and the UK\, the project challenges exclusionary nor
 ms in how games are made. The fellowship offers a EUR 1\,000 honorarium pe
 r fellow over three months (half at start\, half on completion)\; mentorsh
 ip from the core team and advisors in feminist design\, game studies\, 3D 
 production\, and digital culture\; a peer community across NL\, TR\, DE\, 
 and the UK with biweekly meetings\; visibility through a travelling exhibi
 tion program\, publications\, and public events\; and authorship credited 
 in the OAL under its license terms. Five roles are recruited (one fellow e
 ach): 3D Character Artist for inclusive base meshes\; 3D Character Artist 
 for pregnancy and postpartum assets\; 3D Animator for neutral and everyday
  movement\; 3D Modeller for domestic and care-labor environments\; and Res
 earcher/Writer for documentation and the representation framework\; applic
 ants may rank up to two. Open to 3D artists\, animators\, modellers\, desi
 gners\, researchers\, and writers committed to inclusive and intersectiona
 l representation in games\; prior game-industry experience is not required
 \, and emerging creators\, underrepresented practitioners\, and researcher
 s at the intersection of games\, gender\, and culture are especially encou
 raged\, particularly those based in or connected to NL\, TR\, DE\, or the 
 UK. To apply\, email feministgamingproject@gmail.com with a short statemen
 t (max ~500 words)\, a portfolio or work samples (a link is fine)\, and co
 nfirmation of availability for the three-month period\; name the role(s) i
 n the subject line or statement. The project explicitly asks applicants to
  write statements in their own voice rather than using AI-generated text. 
 Indicative timeline: applications close 12 July 2026\; selection and notif
 ication late July\; fellowship period August to October 2026\; showcase an
 d publication November to December 2026.\n\nOrganisation: Feminist Gaming 
 Project\nLocation: Remote across the Netherlands\, Türkiye\, Germany\, an
 d the UK\nAward: EUR 1\,000 honorarium per fellow (paid half at the start\
 , half on completion)\nDuration: Three months\, August to October 2026\; m
 inimum ~6 hours per week (~75 hours total)\n\nMore: https://feministgaming
 .com/fellowship/index.html?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_mediu
 m=referral
URL:https://feministgaming.com/fellowship/index.html?utm_source=artificialn
 ouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Remote across the Netherlands\, Türkiye\, Germany\, and the UK
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:govai-us-ai-policy-program-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260709T211504Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260705
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260706
SUMMARY:Deadline: GovAI U.S. AI Policy Program
DESCRIPTION:The GovAI U.S. AI Policy Program is a bipartisan\, part-time\, 
 12-week program designed to accelerate or launch careers in U.S. AI policy
 . Open to U.S. policy professionals across government and think tanks\, it
  builds a technically-informed understanding of the AI policy landscape th
 rough guided discussion sessions\, with an emphasis on general-purpose AI.
  Topics include how general-purpose AI systems are developed\; inputs to A
 I development such as energy\, chips\, and data centers\; AI's effects on 
 productivity\, scientific discovery\, and economic growth\; national secur
 ity and great power competition\; corporate self-governance\; AI regulatio
 n in other jurisdictions\; and federal and state AI regulatory proposals i
 n the U.S. Participants also have weekly opportunities to question world-l
 eading experts\; prior guest speakers have included White House OSTP staff
 ers\, former frontier-lab employees\, and people who helped draft U.S. sta
 te- and federal-level AI policy proposals. The program runs early Septembe
 r to early December 2026 (break for Thanksgiving week) with a roughly 5-ho
 ur weekly commitment: two hours of synchronous evening sessions (EST)\, he
 ld in-person at GovAI's D.C. office near DuPont Circle or remotely with ca
 meras on\, plus three hours of independent reading and podcasts from a fre
 e syllabus. To list completion on a resume\, participants must attend 9 of
  12 sessions\, write a short policy memo or op-ed\, and pass an interview-
 based exam. Eligible participants include executive and legislative branch
  staff (fellows\, interns\, detailees\, military personnel\, national labo
 ratory personnel) and think-tank policy researchers and affiliates\, acros
 s a range of seniority levels\, with preference for the D.C. metropolitan 
 area\; participants need not currently cover AI but should aspire to a car
 eer in U.S. tech or national security policy. Selection has two stages: an
  online application with six biographical questions\, a resume\, two verba
 l reasoning questions\, and an approximately 7-minute video\; followed by 
 a 30-minute interview in July\, with final decisions in early August.\n\nO
 rganisation: Centre for the Governance of AI (GovAI)\nLocation: Washington
 \, D.C.\, USA (hybrid\; remote participation available)\nAward: Free to pa
 rticipate\; in-person attendees provided dinner (value kept at or below US
 D 20 per session)\nDuration: 12-week part-time program\, early September t
 o early December 2026 (approximately 5 hours per week)\n\nMore: https://ww
 w.governance.ai/post/govai-u-s-ai-policy-program?utm_source=artificialnouv
 eaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.governance.ai/post/govai-u-s-ai-policy-program?utm_source=a
 rtificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Washington\, D.C.\, USA (hybrid\; remote participation available)
END:VEVENT
