UID:cada-walden-fire-station-library-public-art-2026@artificialnouveau.gith
 ub.io
DTSTAMP:20260709T211504Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260728
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260729
SUMMARY:Deadline: Call to Artists: Walden Fire Station and Library (Calgary
  Arts Development)
DESCRIPTION:Calgary Arts Development (CADA) is seeking an artist or artist 
 team to join The City of Calgary's Walden Fire Station and Library project
  team to create permanent public artwork(s) for a combined fire station an
 d library planned for the community of Walden. One artist/artist team will
  be selected with a total project budget of CAD 275\,000 (exclusive of all
  applicable taxes)\; the opportunity is open to local and national profess
 ional artists/artist teams working in various media. ELIGIBILITY: local an
 d national mid-career to late-career professional public artists and artis
 t teams with a minimum of five years' previous experience creating artwork
  in the public realm\; they must have at least three outdoor permanent pub
 lic art installations\, each with a lifespan of over 10 years and a minimu
 m project budget of CAD 150\,000 (see the Canada Council for the Arts defi
 nition of a professional artist). Walden does not currently have an active
  community association\, so the project requires experience in artist-led 
 community engagement and a strong understanding of alternative outreach. A
 rtists must be available to meet the project timelines from September 2026
  to the end of concept and design by July 2027\; fabrication and installat
 ion take place in Phase 2\, starting in the second half of 2027 and contin
 uing into 2028. REWARD: total project budget CAD 275\,000 (artist fee CAD 
 68\,750 + GST)\; CADA is open to adapting the budget breakdown to the arti
 st's approach\, following CARFAC's recommendation of a minimum 20% to the 
 artist's fee\, though the total budget will not be increased. TIMELINE: ap
 plications open 16 June 2026 (9am MT)\; pre-recorded information session p
 osted early July\; application deadline 28 July 2026 (no applications acce
 pted after 1pm MT)\; shortlisted interviews mid-September\; results late S
 eptember 2026. Eligibility questions: walden@calgaryartsdevelopment.com.\n
 \nOrganisation: Calgary Arts Development (CADA)\nLocation: Walden communit
 y\, Calgary\, Alberta\, Canada. Open to local and national (Canadian) prof
 essional artists/artist teams.\nAward: Total project budget of CAD 275\,00
 0 (exclusive of all applicable taxes) for one selected artist/artist team.
  The artist fee for the total project is CAD 68\,750 + GST. Budget breakdo
 wn can be adapted to the artist's approach\, following CARFAC's recommenda
 tion that a minimum 20% of the budget go to the artist's fee\; the total a
 llocated budget will not be increased.\nDuration: Concept and design from 
 September 2026 to end of July 2027\; fabrication and installation (Phase 2
 ) from the second half of 2027 into 2028.\n\nMore: https://calgaryartsdeve
 lopment.com/public-art/opportunities/all/call-to-artists-walden-fire-stati
 on-and-library/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://calgaryartsdevelopment.com/public-art/opportunities/all/call-to
 -artists-walden-fire-station-and-library/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugran
 tdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Walden community\, Calgary\, Alberta\, Canada. Open to local and n
 ational (Canadian) professional artists/artist teams.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:atu-windgate-artist-in-residence-fall-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260709T211504Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260703
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260704
SUMMARY:Deadline: Windgate Artist-in-Residence Fall 2026 (Arkansas Tech Uni
 versity)
DESCRIPTION:The Artist-in-Residence (AIR) program at Arkansas Tech Universi
 ty is an immersive experience within an art and educational community\, in
 tended to advance the careers of practicing artists\, present residents as
  role models for the ATU community\, and strengthen public awareness of th
 e significance of making art and its effect on the surrounding community. 
 The residency takes place over a five-month period\, giving the artist tim
 e and space to focus on the creative process. For Fall 2026\, the program 
 will select an artist to create a public artwork that enhances the ATU cam
 pus\; both two-dimensional and three-dimensional proposals will be conside
 red. The program is supported by a generous grant from the Windgate Charit
 able Foundation. The Department of Art at ATU offers programs in Fine Art\
 , Graphic Design\, Game and Interactive Media Design\, and Art Education\,
  with a facility in Norman Hall featuring a professional gallery\, compute
 r lab\, lecture hall\, and studios for painting\, drawing\, printmaking\, 
 sculpture\, ceramics\, and graphic design. RESIDENCY DETAILS & EXPECTATION
 S: residents must be artists with significant exhibition records\, strong 
 communication skills\, sustained studio practice\, and a desire to engage 
 with the larger campus community\; involvement may include guest lecturing
 \, public talks\, mentoring students\, open studios\, and/or collaborating
  with faculty and students. The resident sometimes teaches one course in 2
 D Design\, 3D Design\, or Introduction to Drawing during their stay when e
 nrollment allows. Artists are expected to commit as a full-time resident f
 or the Fall academic term 2026. BENEFITS: USD 30\,000 stipend (minus fring
 es)\, USD 18\,000 for supplies\, a 2-bed/2-bath campus apartment\, and a l
 arge climate-controlled off-campus studio. Deadline 3 July 2026.\n\nOrgani
 sation: Arkansas Tech University (supported by the Windgate Charitable Fou
 ndation)\nLocation: Russellville\, Arkansas\, United States (Russellville 
 campus\, in the Arkansas River Valley\, about one hour from Little Rock). 
 In-person\, full-time residency.\nAward: USD 30\,000 stipend (minus fringe
 s) plus USD 18\,000 for supplies. Housing provided (a 2-bed\, 2-bath campu
 s apartment) and a large\, climate-controlled\, dedicated off-campus studi
 o space.\nDuration: Five-month residency over the Fall academic term 2026.
 \n\nMore: https://www.atu.edu/academicaffairs/faculty/adjunct/docs/AIR%20A
 D%20FALL%202026.pdf?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=refer
 ral
URL:https://www.atu.edu/academicaffairs/faculty/adjunct/docs/AIR%20AD%20FAL
 L%202026.pdf?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Russellville\, Arkansas\, United States (Russellville campus\, in 
 the Arkansas River Valley\, about one hour from Little Rock). In-person\, 
 full-time residency.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:creative-philadelphia-msb-interpretive-panels-2026@artificialnouveau.gi
 thub.io
DTSTAMP:20260709T211504Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260712
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260713
SUMMARY:Deadline: MSB Interpretive Panels: Public Art Commission (Creative 
 Philadelphia)
DESCRIPTION:Creative Philadelphia announces a call to commission a series o
 f permanent interpretive panels with integrated augmented reality (AR) com
 ponents at the Municipal Services Building in Center City Philadelphia. Th
 e commission is part of a broader initiative that includes an upcoming pub
 lic sculpture of Dr. Sadie T.M. Alexander by artist Vinnie Bagwell. Inspir
 ed by Alexander's groundbreaking legacy in public service\, these interpre
 tive panels will celebrate the City of Philadelphia's municipal employees 
 (past\, present\, and future) and provide deeper context for understanding
  Dr. Alexander's impact\; they will be located in front of the building's 
 landscaped areas\, flanking the upcoming sculpture\, and are intended to c
 omplement and support the overall site experience. SCOPE: an artist team w
 ill design and fabricate four (4) permanent\, sculptural interpretive pane
 ls incorporating augmented reality (AR) elements to expand storytelling be
 yond the physical surface of the artwork. ELIGIBILITY: all interested arti
 sts are invited to apply\; Philadelphia-based artists are strongly encoura
 ged\, though artists from outside the region will be considered\; multiple
  in-person site visits are required and associated travel costs must be co
 vered within the project budget. SELECTION: a two-part process: Part 1 sub
 mission of qualifications\; Part 2 finalist proposals and interviews. Up t
 o three (3) finalists are invited to submit short concept proposals and at
 tend an interview\; at no point should artists submit design proposals. BU
 DGET: USD 250\,000 total (see amount for the required cost breakdown). An 
 Artist Informational Meeting is held via Zoom on 30 June\, 6:00-7:00pm. Ap
 plication questions: paige.phillips@phila.gov. Apply via Submittable. Dead
 line 12 July 2026 (submissions close Monday 13 July 2026\, 6:00 AM).\n\nOr
 ganisation: Creative Philadelphia (Office of Arts\, Culture and the Creati
 ve Economy)\nLocation: Municipal Services Building\, Center City\, Philade
 lphia\, Pennsylvania\, United States. Philadelphia-based artists strongly 
 encouraged\; artists from outside the region considered. Multiple in-perso
 n site visits required (travel costs covered within the project budget).\n
 Award: Total project budget of USD 250\,000\, which must cover: artist fee
 s (18% design fee)\, design and engineering\, fabrication and installation
 \, structural footings/anchoring\, travel and site visits\, AR development
  (software\, hosting\, content production)\, insurance (1%)\, community en
 gagement participation\, and a service warranty keeping content compatible
  with new mobile OS versions for a minimum of 10 years. No application fee
 s.\nDuration: Permanent public artwork commission\; two-part selection pro
 cess.\n\nMore: https://oacce.submittable.com/submit/357418/msb-interpretiv
 e-panels?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://oacce.submittable.com/submit/357418/msb-interpretive-panels?utm
 _source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Municipal Services Building\, Center City\, Philadelphia\, Pennsyl
 vania\, United States. Philadelphia-based artists strongly encouraged\; ar
 tists from outside the region considered. Multiple in-person site visits r
 equired (travel costs covered within the project budget).
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:neiu-art-design-studio-art-residency-2026-2027@artificialnouveau.github
 .io
DTSTAMP:20260709T211504Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260809
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260810
SUMMARY:Deadline: NEIU Art + Design Studio Art Residency 2026-2027
DESCRIPTION:The NEIU Art + Design Studio Art Residency strives to create vi
 sible connections between Northeastern Illinois University's diverse popul
 ation of art and design students and working artists who embody these iden
 tities\, providing insights and inspiration through a dynamic exchange of 
 ideas and techniques. Visiting Artists should demonstrate a commitment to 
 their artistic practice and an interest in engaging with NEIU's students a
 nd creative community. Each Visiting Artist is awarded an honorarium and h
 as full access for a semester to the NEIU Art + Design facilities specific
  to their project\; over the residency they showcase their work in a publi
 c academic forum\, lead a hands-on workshop\, and participate in a Portfol
 io Review Day for NEIU's Art + Design students. FACILITIES (in the Salme H
 arju Steinberg Fine Arts Center) include a Design Studio with the largest 
 collection of Riso drums at any Chicago university\, a Fab Lab (FDM and re
 sin 3D printers\, large-format CNC router\, vinyl cutters\, laser cutters)
 \, a Ceramic Studio (throwing wheels\, glaze room\, electric and gas kilns
 \, raku area)\, a Letterpress Studio (two Vandercook presses\, metal and w
 ood type)\, a Sculpture Studio (wood shop\, clay modeling and spray painti
 ng areas)\, a Photography Studio (analog and digital\, plus a lighting stu
 dio)\, and fully equipped Painting\, Drawing\, and Printmaking studios. BE
 NEFITS: USD 800 honorarium\; facility access based on project focus (Art +
  Tech\, Ceramics\, Drawing\, Painting\, Photography\, Printmaking\, Sculpt
 ure)\, with supplies requestable subject to approval\; and the opportunity
  to exhibit in a group exhibition in the NEIU Fine Arts Center Gallery. PA
 RTICIPATION: lead a 2-hour hands-on workshop for 15-20 students on a topic
  relevant to the project\; give an hour-long artist talk with Q&A\; and se
 rve as a guest panelist for a day-long portfolio review. KEY DATES: open c
 all 2 June - 9 August\; emailed acceptances in October\; Residency Session
  1 runs 25 January - 14 May and Session 2 runs 30 August - 11 December. Ap
 ply via the JotForm application. Deadline 9 August 2026.\n\nOrganisation: 
 Northeastern Illinois University (NEIU)\, Art + Design Department\nLocatio
 n: Salme Harju Steinberg Fine Arts Center\, Northeastern Illinois Universi
 ty\, Chicago\, Illinois\, United States. In-person\; semester-long access 
 to NEIU facilities.\nAward: USD 800 honorarium\, plus a semester of full a
 ccess to NEIU Art + Design facilities specific to the project (Art + Tech\
 , Ceramics\, Drawing\, Painting\, Photography\, Printmaking\, Sculpture)\;
  supplies can be requested with guidance and approval from Studio Area per
 sonnel. Visiting Artists may also exhibit in a group exhibition in the NEI
 U Fine Arts Center Gallery.\nDuration: One semester. Residency Session 1: 
 25 January - 14 May\; Session 2: 30 August - 11 December.\n\nMore: https:/
 /form.jotform.com/261044627286156?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&ut
 m_medium=referral
URL:https://form.jotform.com/261044627286156?utm_source=artificialnouveaugr
 antdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Salme Harju Steinberg Fine Arts Center\, Northeastern Illinois Uni
 versity\, Chicago\, Illinois\, United States. In-person\; semester-long ac
 cess to NEIU facilities.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:art-shanty-projects-performances-art-actions-2027@artificialnouveau.git
 hub.io
DTSTAMP:20260709T211504Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260709
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260710
SUMMARY:Deadline: Art Shanty Projects 2027: Call for Performances + Art Act
 ions
DESCRIPTION:Art Shanty Projects seeks winter enthusiasts and creative adven
 turers to create performances and art actions for its 2027 Program on Bde 
 Uman (Lake Harriet) in Minneapolis. It invites music-makers\, poets\, buil
 ders\, scientists\, dancers\, puppeteers\, writers\, dreamers\, activists\
 , outdoors-people\, conversationalists\, craftspeople\, storytellers\, and
  more to propose new and innovative ways to engage artistically with the p
 ublic in the social context of a village on a frozen lake (or winter 'beac
 h'\, as climate change may necessitate). ASP has an expansive notion of wh
 at constitutes a performance or art action\, having welcomed dance\, creat
 ive sporting events\, happenings\, carnival games\, music\, roving dance\,
  temporary sculpture\, puppet shows\, artful haircuts\, advice booths\, cl
 imate actions\, and more. NOTE: this call is for PERFORMANCES + ART ACTION
 S only (a separate call exists for shanty artists). Since 2004\, Art Shant
 y Projects has created joyful winter art experiences inspired by pop-up ic
 e fishing villages\, using the frozen lake as a public platform for a temp
 orary creative community with tens of thousands of annual visitors. ASP is
  deeply committed to social\, racial\, gender\, and economic justice and t
 o accessibility (embracing the spirit of the ADA). ELIGIBILITY: everyone i
 s eligible (artists at all career stages)\; applicants need not have exper
 ience with everything asked\, but should show eagerness to engage\, develo
 p new skills\, and stay open to new perspectives. Projects that involve se
 lling anything or the exchange of legal currency will not be accepted. COM
 PENSATION: sliding-scale stipend up to USD 1\,000 plus extensive productio
 n and logistical support. PROGRAM: on-ice every Saturday and Sunday\, 10am
 -4pm\, 16 January to 7 February 2027\; selected artists notified mid-Augus
 t 2026\, with mandatory in-person meetings (at least one team member) star
 ting 10 September 2026. Apply via the Google form (preferred) or the no-Go
 ogle-account alternative. Contact Erin Lavelle\, Artistic Director: progra
 m@artshantyprojects.org. Deadline for proposal submissions: 9 July 2026\, 
 11:59pm CST.\n\nOrganisation: Art Shanty Projects\nLocation: Bde Uman (Lak
 e Harriet)\, Minneapolis\, Minnesota\, United States. On-ice program plus 
 several mandatory in-person meetings in Minneapolis\; in-person participat
 ion required.\nAward: Sliding-scale stipend up to USD 1\,000 (request an a
 mount that fits the project: roughly USD 1\,000 for full-day/most-ambitiou
 s activities\, USD 500 for half-day\, USD 250 for short or one-off/solo/lo
 w-production activities). Plus direct production support\, discounted mate
 rials and resource sharing\, a shared warming shanty\, a hot meal\, snacks
 \, hot beverages\, hand/toe warmers\, one parking space per project\, on-s
 ite medic\, and ASL interpreter/audio describer for the public. No applica
 tion fees.\nDuration: On-ice program every Saturday and Sunday\, 10am-4pm\
 , 16 January to 7 February 2027\, with production meetings and mandatory c
 heck-ins from September 2026 onward.\n\nMore: https://artshantyprojects.or
 g/2027-call-for-performances-art-actions/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugran
 tdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://artshantyprojects.org/2027-call-for-performances-art-actions/?u
 tm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Bde Uman (Lake Harriet)\, Minneapolis\, Minnesota\, United States.
  On-ice program plus several mandatory in-person meetings in Minneapolis\;
  in-person participation required.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:rps-eamonn-mccabe-bursary-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260709T211504Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260803
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260804
SUMMARY:Deadline: Eamonn McCabe Bursary 2026 (Royal Photographic Society)
DESCRIPTION:The Eamonn McCabe Bursary\, launched in 2024\, commemorates the
  life of photojournalist Eamonn McCabe (1948-2022)\, who made his name as 
 a sports photographer before moving to wider editorial work\, mainly for T
 he Observer and The Guardian\, and who supported a generation of photograp
 hers from the 1980s to the 2020s. Run by the RPS in partnership with McCab
 e's family and The Guardian\, this international bursary continues that le
 gacy. AWARD: GBP 3\,000 to a photographer aged 30 years or under to delive
 r a photography project responding to the theme of 'sporting endeavour'\, 
 which can be interpreted as widely as the applicant wishes\, though the ge
 neral approach should be suitable for publication. The project should norm
 ally be new\, not previously exhibited or published. As well as profession
 al sports\, the call particularly encourages projects covering grassroots 
 and community activities (for example\, addressing issues such as mental h
 ealth or supporting displaced communities)\, and welcomes creative interpr
 etations of the theme. The completed project will be published by The Guar
 dian and the RPS. ELIGIBILITY: applicants must be aged 30 years or under o
 n the closing date. PROCESS: interviews via Zoom in September\; recipient 
 announced by the end of September\; project completed within one year of a
 ward. Apply via the RPS application portal using RPS Account credentials. 
 Closing date 3 August 2026.\n\nOrganisation: The Royal Photographic Societ
 y (RPS)\, in partnership with Eamonn McCabe's family and The Guardian\nLoc
 ation: International bursary. Applicants must be aged 30 years or under on
  the closing date. Interviews held via Zoom.\nAward: GBP 3\,000 to deliver
  a photography project on the theme of 'sporting endeavour'. The completed
  project will be published by The Guardian and the RPS\, who will work wit
 h the recipient to bring the project to a wider audience.\nDuration: The p
 roject should be completed within one year of being awarded.\n\nMore: http
 s://rps.org/opportunities/bursaries/eamonn-mccabe-bursary/?utm_source=arti
 ficialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
