UID:genesis-mission-ai-fellowship-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260709T211504Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260731
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260801
SUMMARY:Deadline: Genesis Mission AI Fellowship 2026
DESCRIPTION:The Horizon Institute for Public Service\, Renaissance Philanth
 ropy\, SeedAI\, and Fulcrum Science are partnering to launch a fellowship 
 that embeds technical AI talent across the US Department of Energy nationa
 l labs to advance the goals of the Genesis Mission\, DOE's flagship scienc
 e and technology initiative launched in late 2025. The Genesis Mission ide
 ntifies 26 national science and technology challenges critical to US leade
 rship and envisions a national platform connecting supercomputers\, experi
 mental facilities\, AI systems\, and unique datasets\, with DOE's 17 natio
 nal labs playing a key role. Genesis Mission AI Fellows are forward deploy
 ed to DOE national labs to bring frontier AI expertise to high-priority sc
 ientific challenges. As core members of the technical staff on a Genesis M
 ission project\, fellows work alongside national lab scientists and partne
 rs and apply AI to national priorities\, from building cutting-edge models
  of plasma dynamics in pursuit of controlled fusion to advancing state-of-
 the-art models for foundational materials discovery. Initial national lab 
 partners include Idaho National Laboratory\, Brookhaven National Laborator
 y\, and the Princeton Plasma Physics Laboratory\; additional partners may 
 be announced later. COMPENSATION/DURATION: 9-12 months starting fall 2026\
 , with a prorated total annual compensation of USD 200\,000\; fellows are 
 expected to travel to their national lab site at least once a quarter but 
 may work on-site if they prefer. ELIGIBILITY: competitive applicants shoul
 d have at least 2 years of industry experience building AI models or agent
 s (those with industry experience building AI applications or data infrast
 ructure will also be considered)\; scientific domain expertise is not requ
 ired\, but any placement will involve some training and study in a specifi
 c scientific discipline or energy topic\, supported by expert colleagues a
 t the host institution. All fellows must be eligible to work in the United
  States for the duration of the placement\; US employment visas cannot be 
 sponsored\, but US permanent residents (green card holders) are eligible. 
 APPLICATION: initial form requires a CV or resume (max 2 pages) and short-
 answer questions on motivations and experiences (max 200 words)\; successf
 ul applicants complete interviews through partner organizations and nation
 al labs\, and selected fellows are matched to partner labs by scientific d
 omain and availability. The review uses evidence-based best practices incl
 uding blind grading of application materials. TIMELINE: application deadli
 ne 31 July 2026\; final fellow selection August-September 2026\; expected 
 start fall 2026.\n\nOrganisation: Horizon Institute for Public Service (wi
 th Renaissance Philanthropy\, SeedAI\, and Fulcrum Science)\nLocation: Uni
 ted States. Fellows are forward deployed to US Department of Energy nation
 al labs (initial partners: Idaho National Laboratory\, Brookhaven National
  Laboratory\, Princeton Plasma Physics Laboratory). Remote or in-person\; 
 on-site travel at least once a quarter. Must be eligible to work in the US
  (no visa sponsorship\; US green card holders eligible).\nAward: Prorated 
 total annual compensation of USD 200\,000.\nDuration: 9-12 months\, starti
 ng fall 2026.\n\nMore: https://horizonpublicservice.org/announcing-the-gen
 esis-mission-ai-fellowship/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medi
 um=referral
URL:https://horizonpublicservice.org/announcing-the-genesis-mission-ai-fell
 owship/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:United States. Fellows are forward deployed to US Department of En
 ergy national labs (initial partners: Idaho National Laboratory\, Brookhav
 en National Laboratory\, Princeton Plasma Physics Laboratory). Remote or i
 n-person\; on-site travel at least once a quarter. Must be eligible to wor
 k in the US (no visa sponsorship\; US green card holders eligible).
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:ddc-trygfonden-fellowship-2027@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260709T211504Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260901
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260902
SUMMARY:Deadline: Digital Democracy Centre x TrygFonden Fellowship Program 
 2027
DESCRIPTION:The Digital Democracy Centre (DDC) at the University of Souther
 n Denmark\, with support from TrygFonden\, is calling for applications for
  its 2027 fellowship cohort. The program fosters collaboration between res
 earchers\, journalists\, and policymakers exploring the impact of digital 
 technology and AI on media\, politics\, and democracy. Fellows collaborate
  with a self-selected DDC mentor to generate new knowledge\, contribute to
  public debate\, develop networks\, and produce tangible outreach outputs 
 such as policy briefs\, educational packages\, and talks. THREE FELLOWSHIP
  TYPES: (1) academic fellows researching digital technologies and democrac
 y\; (2) journalist fellows covering digital technology and democracy\; (3)
  policy fellows contributing to the regulatory debate. Target group: resea
 rchers\, journalism graduates\, and policymakers in research/educational i
 nstitutions\, media organizations\, ministries\, NGOs\, etc. PRIORITIES: p
 rojects with clear relevance to Denmark or Danish society (including compa
 rative/international projects yielding insights relevant to a Danish conte
 xt)\; in 2027\, projects related to DDC's Hybrid Warfare Initiative (socie
 tal resilience to new forms of international conflict\, with a focus on di
 gital technologies and AI) are also prioritized. EXPECTATIONS: applicants 
 must secure confirmation of mentorship from their desired DDC mentor BEFOR
 E applying (applications without a confirmed mentor are automatically reje
 cted\; PhD students and research assistants are generally not eligible as 
 mentors\, and Sten Schaumburg-Muller is unavailable as a mentor for the 20
 27 call)\; applicants must also coordinate support from their current supe
 rvisors/managers. Fellows engage in DDC activities\, seminars/workshops\, 
 and public outreach\, and submit a short report within two months of finis
 hing. APPLICATION (in English): preliminary project title\, fellowship typ
 e\, brief project description (max 1000 chars)\, detailed description and 
 timeline (max 2400 chars\, including duration\, confirmed mentor\, and rem
 ote/in-office work plan)\, description of activities and collaboration wit
 h external practice partners (max 1000 chars)\, expected product/impact/ou
 tput (max 500 chars)\, a CV (max 5 pages)\, and an overview of the posts f
 or which financial support is sought. Submit the application form (PDF or 
 Word) plus CV as PDFs to ddc@sdu.dk with subject line 'DDC / TrygFonden Fe
 llowship application'. Deadline 1 September 2026\; decisions communicated 
 no later than 1 October 2026.\n\nOrganisation: Digital Democracy Centre (U
 niversity of Southern Denmark)\, with support from TrygFonden\nLocation: O
 dense\, Denmark (University of Southern Denmark). Flexible mix of in-offic
 e stays at the DDC in Odense and remote periods\; stays planned to the Dan
 ish working calendar.\nAward: Either a salary subsidy or a stipend to help
  with travel and/or housing\; specific benefits (financial support\, acces
 s to DDC research resources\, flexible working spaces\, speaker series\, n
 etworks) vary by agreement between the fellow\, DDC\, and partnering organ
 izations. Applicants describe the posts they seek support for (flights\, h
 ousing\, research costs\, salary compensation\, stipend\, etc.).\nDuration
 : Flexible\; typically 2-6 months (minimum two months\, can include shorte
 r DDC stays and remote periods)\, longer in exceptional cases. Fellowships
  start anywhere in 2027.\n\nMore: https://www.sdu.dk/en/forskning/forsknin
 gsenheder/samf/digitaldemocracycentre/news+folder/ddcxtrygfonden-fellowshi
 p-call-2027?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.sdu.dk/en/forskning/forskningsenheder/samf/digitaldemocracy
 centre/news+folder/ddcxtrygfonden-fellowship-call-2027?utm_source=artifici
 alnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Odense\, Denmark (University of Southern Denmark). Flexible mix of
  in-office stays at the DDC in Odense and remote periods\; stays planned t
 o the Danish working calendar.
END:VEVENT
