BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:effea-call-5-get-ready-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260709T211504Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20261103
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20261104
SUMMARY:Deadline: EFFEA Call #5: European Festivals Fund for Emerging Artis
 ts
DESCRIPTION:The European Festivals Fund for Emerging Artists (EFFEA)\, an i
 nitiative of the European Festivals Association co-funded by the European 
 Union\, will open its fifth call from 1 September to 3 November 2026\, wit
 h full guidelines and application details published on 1 September 2026. C
 all #5 will again support around 50 cross-border co-production residencies
  taking place in 2027\, each bringing together at least three festivals fr
 om different eligible countries to accompany an emerging artist or collect
 ive. EFFEA is a co-production residency scheme: festivals join forces acro
 ss borders to support an emerging artist through a process of creation and
  presentation\, providing dedicated time\, space\, and tailored mentoring\
 , exchange\, and collaboration\, moving beyond a single invitation toward 
 a shared artistic development journey. Each supported project is built aro
 und one leading festival working with at least two partner festivals based
  in different eligible countries\; one emerging artist or collective at th
 e centre\; a combination of artistic development\, mentoring\, exchange\, 
 and audience engagement based on the artist's needs\; and presentations or
  outcomes shared across the partner festivals. Two residency formats are o
 ffered. DISCOVERY (EUR 8\,000 grant): the proposal must include a workshop
  (live or online) hosted by the leading festival with at least one program
 mer from each partner festival\, and a work-in-progress presentation at th
 e leading festival. SPRINGBOARD (EUR 15\,000 grant): the proposal must inc
 lude final presentations or production results shown within each festival 
 (minimum the leading festival plus two partners) and a live masterclass le
 d by the artist(s) at each festival (minimum the leading festival plus two
  partners). WHO CAN APPLY: festivals that have existed for at least one ed
 ition and are registered on FestivalFinder.eu\; the festivals apply on beh
 alf of the residency project. Residency projects must fall within these ar
 tistic fields: architecture\, ballet\, contemporary dance\, circus\, desig
 n/applied arts\, digital arts\, film\, folklore and folk arts\, heritage\,
  interdisciplinary\, literature\, music\, opera\, street art\, theatre\, p
 hotography/video\, puppetry\, sculpture\, painting. A series of EFFEA info
 \, networking\, and Q&A sessions runs on Tuesdays 11:00-12:00 CEST (15 Sep
 tember\, 29 September\, 13 October\, and 20 October 2026) to help applican
 ts navigate the process and find partners. Across Calls #1 to #4\, EFFEA h
 as supported 619 festivals and 200 artists/collectives across Europe and b
 eyond.\n\nOrganisation: European Festivals Association (EFA)\nLocation: Ac
 ross eligible European countries\; residencies built around partner festiv
 als registered on FestivalFinder.eu\nAward: Per-residency grants: EUR 8\,0
 00 (Discovery format) or EUR 15\,000 (Springboard format)\nDuration: Resid
 encies take place in 2027\; call open 1 September to 3 November 2026\, ful
 l guidelines published 1 September 2026\n\nMore: https://www.effea.eu/news
 /item/2026/06/24/effea-call-5-get-ready?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantd
 esk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.effea.eu/news/item/2026/06/24/effea-call-5-get-ready?utm_so
 urce=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Across eligible European countries\; residencies built around part
 ner festivals registered on FestivalFinder.eu
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:stiftung-kuenstlerdorf-schoeppingen-fellowship-2027@artificialnouveau.g
 ithub.io
DTSTAMP:20260709T211504Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260831
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260901
SUMMARY:Deadline: Stiftung Künstler*dorf Schöppingen: Residency Fellowshi
 p 2027 Open Call
DESCRIPTION:Stiftung Künstler*dorf Schöppingen offers residency fellowshi
 ps for professional visual artists\, authors and composers\; since 2023 ap
 plications from collectives are also accepted. The call is open to people 
 of all nationalities and ages\, and accommodation for partners\, family me
 mbers or assistance can be arranged upon agreement and availability (for p
 hysical\, cognitive or sensory disabilities\, contact the foundation to ex
 plain any barriers). Fellows reside and work at the Künstler*dorf for a p
 eriod of their choosing between two and six months\, using the premises an
 d infrastructure on-site. The stipend is EUR 1\,500 per month\, minus roug
 hly EUR 100-200 for rent and operating expenses\; for collectives it is EU
 R 1\,000 per person up to a maximum of EUR 3\,000 per month\, minus rent a
 nd operating costs. Travel\, insurance or material costs are covered only 
 in exceptional cases on request. The fellowship is not designed as a produ
 ction residency and there is no obligation to present results\, though exh
 ibition and presentation facilities are available and the voluntary co-org
 anization of events (lectures\, readings\, workshops or similar) is welcom
 ed. A willingness to participate in events and to engage in exchange with 
 other fellows is a prerequisite. Selection is made by expert juries on the
  quality of previous work\, the quality and plausibility of the project fo
 r Schöppingen\, and program contributions (interaction / community buildi
 ng). Applications for 2027 can be submitted from 27 June to 31 August 2026
  (midnight CET) via the online application portal.\n\nOrganisation: Stiftu
 ng Künstler*dorf Schöppingen\nLocation: Schöppingen\, Germany (residenc
 y requires living and working on-site)\nAward: Stipend of EUR 1\,500 per m
 onth\, minus roughly EUR 100-200 for rent and operating expenses. For coll
 ectives\, EUR 1\,000 per person up to a maximum of EUR 3\,000 per month\, 
 minus rent and operating costs. Travel\, insurance and material costs are 
 covered only in exceptional cases\, on request.\nDuration: Residency of tw
 o to six months during 2027\; period chosen by agreement and availability\
 n\nMore: https://stiftung-kuenstlerdorf.de/en/application_process?utm_sour
 ce=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://stiftung-kuenstlerdorf.de/en/application_process?utm_source=art
 ificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Schöppingen\, Germany (residency requires living and working on-s
 ite)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:phenomenon-grant-kerenidis-pepe-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260709T211504Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260930
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20261001
SUMMARY:Deadline: Phenomenon Grant 2026 (Second Edition)
DESCRIPTION:Created in 2025\, the Phenomenon Grant is a yearly program that
  supports art projects in Greece with grants of EUR 5\,000 to EUR 10\,000 
 for individuals\, collectives\, and non-profit organizations engaged with 
 queer\, feminist\, anti-colonial\, and other emancipatory art practices. T
 he grant aims to support critical phases of artistic development\, enablin
 g experimentation\, research\, collaboration\, and the realization of new 
 and ongoing projects. In a context marked by rising authoritarianism\, gen
 ocidal forces and the dismantling of social justice advancements\, the pro
 gram seeks to support voices that critically and ethically engage with the
 se issues\, create spaces of resistance\, reimagine futures beyond exclusi
 on\, persecution\, and domination\, and open pathways toward collective li
 beration. Particular attention is paid to collaborative endeavours rooted 
 in Greece that are built on connections with the Global Majority\, promoti
 ng networks of translocal solidarity and interconnected struggles. Organiz
 ed and supported by Kerenidis Pepe\, which has pledged a total budget of E
 UR 60\,000 over 2025-2027\, the amount awarded is based on the application
 's actual funding needs. In 2025 the program received 193 applications and
  awarded three grants of EUR 8\,500 each to Athens Museum of Queer Arts (A
 MOQA)\, Forensic Architecture Initiative Athens (FAIA) and Theo Panagopoul
 os. The 2026 selection committee is composed of Athena Athanasiou\, Dora G
 arcia\, Christina Li\, VASKOS\, and chaired by Aggelika Mitsiou. The submi
 ssion period runs from 1 September to 30 September 2026\, with selected pr
 ojects announced in November 2026.\n\nOrganisation: Phenomenon Association
 \, supported by Kerenidis Pepe\nLocation: Greece (projects rooted in Greec
 e)\nAward: Grants ranging from EUR 5\,000 to EUR 10\,000\, based on the ap
 plication's actual funding needs. Each edition awards a minimum of EUR 20\
 ,000 to two to four grantees (in 2025\, three grants of EUR 8\,500 each we
 re awarded).\nDuration: One- or two-year initiatives\; selected projects a
 nnounced November 2026\n\nMore: https://kerenidispepe.art/projects/grants/
 ?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://kerenidispepe.art/projects/grants/?utm_source=artificialnouveau
 grantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Greece (projects rooted in Greece)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:pee-workshop-matter-out-of-place-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260709T211504Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260810
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260811
SUMMARY:Deadline: Open Call: Pee Workshop (Matter Out of Place)
DESCRIPTION:Pee Workshop is looking for 16 performers to take part in a two
 -day research practice led by Nica Roses and Eris Kyriakides as part of th
 e dance and performance event Matter Out of Place. The workshop uses drink
 ing\, holding\, and releasing liquid as a starting point for choreographic
  research\, paying attention to the body's internal timing: what we consum
 e\, how liquid moves through the body\, what the bladder signals\, and how
  the organs produce movements that often go unnoticed. This cycle becomes 
 the structure of the research\, opening into dance\, somatic exercises\, c
 horeographic tasks\, group compositions\, and experiments with collective 
 energy. The material develops through urination but also through the share
 d experience of moving\, waiting\, responding\, and performing together. P
 erformers\, dancers\, movement practitioners\, and artists interested in s
 omatic research\, experimental choreography\, and collective performance-m
 aking are welcome\; professional dance training is not required\, but appl
 icants should feel comfortable working physically and collaboratively. All
  exercises are approached through clear consent\, respect for personal bou
 ndaries\, and collective care. The workshop takes place Monday 17 and Tues
 day 18 August 2026 from 10:00 to 17:00 at The Dirty Art Foundation\, culmi
 nating in an optional 60-minute public showing on Wednesday 19 August. Eac
 h performer receives a fee of EUR 200. To apply\, send a short introductio
 n about yourself\, your movement or performance experience\, and why you a
 re interested in the workshop to nicaxroses@gmail.com by 10 August 2026.\n
 \nOrganisation: Nica Roses & Eris Kyriakides\, at The Dirty Art Foundation
 \nLocation: The Dirty Art Foundation (Amsterdam\, Netherlands)\nAward: Per
 former fee of EUR 200. Participation in the optional public showing is not
  required to receive the fee.\nDuration: Two-day workshop\, Monday 17 and 
 Tuesday 18 August 2026\, 10:00-17:00\, with an optional 60-minute public s
 howing on Wednesday 19 August\n\nMore: https://www.instagram.com/p/DacdGWT
 jTSL/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.instagram.com/p/DacdGWTjTSL/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugr
 antdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:The Dirty Art Foundation (Amsterdam\, Netherlands)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:princeton-hodder-fellowship-2027-2028@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260709T211504Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260908
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260909
SUMMARY:Deadline: The Hodder Fellowship 2027-2028 (Princeton University)
DESCRIPTION:The Hodder Fellowship is given to artists and writers of except
 ional promise to pursue independent projects at Princeton University durin
 g the academic year. Potential Hodder Fellows are composers\, choreographe
 rs\, performance artists\, visual artists\, writers\, translators\, or oth
 er kinds of artists or humanists who have 'much more than ordinary intelle
 ctual and literary gifts'\; they are selected more 'for promise than for p
 erformance.' Given the strength of the applicant pool\, most successful Fe
 llows have published a first book or have similar achievements in their ow
 n fields\; the Hodder is designed to provide Fellows with the 'studious le
 isure' to undertake significant new work. Fellows spend an academic year a
 t Princeton with no formal teaching\, supported by a USD 93\,000 stipend f
 or the 10-month Visiting Fellow appointment. IMPORTANT: for this cycle\, a
 pplications are accepted only for the Program in Dance\, the Program in Th
 eater and Music Theater\, the Program in Visual Arts\, and the Department 
 of Music. Fellowships are not intended to fund work leading to an advanced
  degree\; one need not be a U.S. citizen to apply\; previous recipients of
  the Princeton Arts Fellowship are not eligible. To apply\, submit a resum
 e\, a 500-word project proposal\, and samples of your work (writing sample
 \, images\, video links to performances\, etc.). Applicants may apply for 
 the Hodder Fellowship only twice in a lifetime. The application cycle clos
 es 8 September 2026 at 11:59 p.m. EDT.\n\nOrganisation: Princeton Universi
 ty\, Lewis Center for the Arts\nLocation: Princeton\, New Jersey\, USA\; a
 cademic-year appointment as a Visiting Fellow (no U.S. citizenship require
 d)\nAward: USD 93\,000 stipend for the 10-month appointment as a Visiting 
 Fellow. No formal teaching is involved.\nDuration: One academic year (10-m
 onth appointment)\, 2027-2028\n\nMore: https://arts.princeton.edu/fellowsh
 ips/hodder-fellowship/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=re
 ferral
URL:https://arts.princeton.edu/fellowships/hodder-fellowship/?utm_source=ar
 tificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Princeton\, New Jersey\, USA\; academic-year appointment as a Visi
 ting Fellow (no U.S. citizenship required)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:accent-sisters-work-study-fellowship-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260709T211504Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260801
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260802
SUMMARY:Deadline: Accent Sisters Work-Study Fellowship Program 2026
DESCRIPTION:Accent Sisters offers a work-study fellowship for individuals p
 assionate about literature\, visual arts\, and community engagement. The f
 ellowship provides hands-on experience in a bookstore and a hybrid event s
 pace where exhibitions\, book launches\, film screenings\, educational pro
 grams\, and other public programming take place. It is ideal for someone l
 ooking to build a career in cultural institutions\, independent bookstores
 \, or art galleries. Fellows work closely with both the bookstore and gall
 ery teams\, gaining skills in book curation\, exhibit planning\, marketing
 \, and community outreach\, while developing a personal project that merge
 s these disciplines. WHAT YOU GET: opportunities to work with writers\, ar
 tists\, and creators\; a chance to pitch projects\, events\, and programs 
 for a diverse community\; free passes to all in-person events and classes\
 ; fellow discounts\; a showcase of your personal project toward the end of
  the fellowship\; one-on-one mentorship with the Accent team\; and a USD 6
 00 stipend. Open to upcoming seniors\, upcoming second-year graduate stude
 nts\, and recent graduates of undergraduate/graduate programs. Four tracks
  are offered and applicants generally choose one: Program Coordination & C
 ommunity Engagement\; Curation & Administration\; Graphic Design & Digital
  Asset Management\; or Marketing & Business Development. The fellowship ru
 ns 20 August to 20 December 2026 (part-time\, 3 days per week\, on-site re
 quired). Applications are reviewed from 15 July to 1 August 2026.\n\nOrgan
 isation: Accent Sisters\nLocation: 89 5th Ave\, Suite 702\, New York\, NY 
 10003 (hybrid\; part-time\, 3 days/week\, on-site work required)\nAward: S
 tipend of USD 600 (paid in two installments)\, plus free passes to all in-
 person events and classes\, fellow discounts\, and one-on-one mentorship.\
 nDuration: 20 August to 20 December 2026\; part-time\, 3 days per week\n\n
 More: https://www.accentaccent.com/page/fellowship?utm_source=artificialno
 uveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.accentaccent.com/page/fellowship?utm_source=artificialnouve
 augrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:89 5th Ave\, Suite 702\, New York\, NY 10003 (hybrid\; part-time\,
  3 days/week\, on-site work required)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:singapore-ai-safety-fellowship-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260709T211504Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260710
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260711
SUMMARY:Deadline: The Singapore AI Safety Fellowship 2026
DESCRIPTION:The Singapore AI Safety Fellowship is an independent research f
 ellowship that connects fellows with leading mentors working on technical 
 AI safety and governance. Fellows conduct research for three months in Sin
 gapore (21 September to 4 December 2026)\, building the skills and relatio
 nships for international coordination on AI safety. It is built for resear
 chers who want their work to inform real-world AI safety practice on top o
 f publishing it\, drawing on Singapore's role as a globally connected\, po
 licy-engaged hub. The program rests on three pillars: cross-regional colla
 boration (bringing together researchers from East and West to build truste
 d relationships for sustained cross-border AI safety collaboration)\; tech
 nical depth and research excellence (guided by experienced researchers and
  advisors\, fellows investigate pressing challenges in making frontier AI 
 systems safe\, secure\, and trustworthy)\; and applying research to policy
  (institutional partnerships that ground projects in real-world applicatio
 n and help fellows translate technical ideas into practical frameworks and
  policy recommendations). Advisors include Zhang Ya-Qin (Chair Professor\,
  Tsinghua University\; Founding Dean of the Institute for AI Industry Rese
 arch) and Ryan Kidd (Co-Executive Director\, MATS Program). Fellows receiv
 e weekly mentorship from established AI safety researchers\, dedicated Res
 earch Managers\, a stipend of SGD 5\,000 per month with housing provided t
 hroughout\, up to USD 30\,000 in compute for projects that require it\, ce
 ntral office space at SASH's hub in Chinatown\, and a community of talks\,
  workshops\, and social events. The application deadline is 10 July 2026.\
 n\nOrganisation: Singapore AI Safety Hub (SASH)\nLocation: Singapore (thre
 e-month in-person fellowship\, 21 September - 4 December 2026)\nAward: Sti
 pend of SGD 5\,000 per month\, plus housing and travel. Up to USD 30\,000 
 in compute per project. Includes mentorship\, research management support\
 , and central office space in Chinatown.\nDuration: Three months in Singap
 ore\, 21 September to 4 December 2026\n\nMore: https://www.aisafety.sg/pro
 grams/singapore-ai-safety-fellowship?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk
 &utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.aisafety.sg/programs/singapore-ai-safety-fellowship?utm_sou
 rce=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Singapore (three-month in-person fellowship\, 21 September - 4 Dec
 ember 2026)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:mountainfilm-commitment-grants-emerging-filmmaker-fellowship-2026@artif
 icialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260709T211504Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260716
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260717
SUMMARY:Deadline: Mountainfilm: Commitment Grants & Emerging Filmmaker Fell
 owship
DESCRIPTION:Mountainfilm's Commitment Grants support documentary filmmakers
  with projects in post-production\, with over USD 90\,000 in funding this 
 cycle for films that celebrate adventure\, activism\, social justice\, cul
 ture\, the environment\, and indomitable spirit. Mountainfilm actively enc
 ourages diversity behind the camera\, and a portion of funding is set asid
 e for two focus areas: projects featuring an LGBTQ+ protagonist or a story
  about overcoming personal challenges\, societal stigmas\, and/or communit
 y obstacles with a meaningful connection to the outdoors or nature-based p
 ursuits\; and projects exploring immigration or migration\, or created by 
 immigrant or first-generation immigrant filmmakers. AWARDS: individual Com
 mitment Grants range from USD 3\,000 to 6\,000. EMERGING FILMMAKER FELLOWS
 HIP: one early-career filmmaker is selected from the Commitment Grant appl
 icant pool for a yearlong mentorship that includes edit and story consulta
 tion\, networking opportunities\, a cash award\, and a funded trip to Tell
 uride during the festival over Memorial Day weekend (travel\, lodging\, an
 d a Mountainfilm pass\, applicable to the year following the award). ELIGI
 BILITY: Commitment Grants are open to applicants from any country\; the Em
 erging Filmmaker Fellowship accepts applicants from any country but requir
 es current U.S. residency. Post-production projects only\, completed\, rel
 eased\, or festival-screened projects are not eligible\, and impact campai
 gns are not funded. Prior Commitment Grant recipients should not re-apply 
 for the same project\; previously declined projects may re-apply only with
  substantial changes. REQUIREMENTS: a video sample or trailer of the curre
 nt project no longer than 10 minutes (password-protected Vimeo links prefe
 rred)\; the screener link must stay active and cannot be changed after sub
 mission. The Emerging Filmmaker application additionally requires a direct
 or bio\, headshot\, and cover letter. Recipients are expected to provide p
 rogress updates 2-3 times a year\, include Mountainfilm recognition in cre
 dits\, and discuss premiere consideration with the programming team. TIMEL
 INE: applications are open July 1 to July 16\, 2026 (closing 11:59 PM MDT)
 \, with notifications in late August or early September. Questions: entrie
 s@mountainfilm.org.\n\nOrganisation: Mountainfilm\nLocation: Application o
 nline\; Telluride\, Colorado\, United States (fellowship trip during the f
 estival). Commitment Grants are open to filmmakers from any country\; the 
 Emerging Filmmaker Fellowship requires current U.S. residency.\nAward: Ove
 r USD 90\,000 in total funding. Individual Commitment Grants range from US
 D 3\,000 to 6\,000. The Emerging Filmmaker Fellowship adds a yearlong ment
 orship\, a cash award\, and a funded trip to Telluride over Memorial Day w
 eekend (travel\, lodging\, and a festival pass).\nDuration: Commitment Gra
 nts support projects in post-production\; the Emerging Filmmaker Fellowshi
 p is a yearlong mentorship.\n\nMore: https://www.mountainfilm.org/mountain
 film-initiatives/commitment-grants/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&
 utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.mountainfilm.org/mountainfilm-initiatives/commitment-grants
 /?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Application online\; Telluride\, Colorado\, United States (fellows
 hip trip during the festival). Commitment Grants are open to filmmakers fr
 om any country\; the Emerging Filmmaker Fellowship requires current U.S. r
 esidency.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:horizon-ai-rapid-response-fellowship-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260709T211504Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260722
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260723
SUMMARY:Deadline: Horizon Institute for Public Service: AI Rapid Response F
 ellowship
DESCRIPTION:The AI Rapid Response Fellowship is a focused effort by the Hor
 izon Institute for Public Service to close the AI security talent gap in t
 he U.S. federal government. Horizon is recruiting a specialized cohort of 
 exceptional technical and policy talent to work full-time in executive bra
 nch offices on AI security-related issues\, with placements beginning as s
 oon as possible. TRACKS: the Fellow track is for candidates with technical
  or policy expertise relevant to AI security\, typically 2-6+ years of ful
 l-time relevant experience\; the Senior Fellow track is for candidates wit
 h substantial prior experience\, typically 10-15+ years in relevant techni
 cal\, policy\, or leadership roles. FOCUS: AI governance\, AI security\, p
 olicy\, and public service. COMPENSATION: Fellow track USD 170\,000-200\,0
 00+ plus a benefits stipend\; Senior Fellow track from USD 250\,000+ plus 
 a benefits stipend\, commensurate with the seniority of the placement. DUR
 ATION: one year full-time\, with the opportunity for renewal\, based in th
 e Washington\, DC area. ELIGIBILITY: U.S. citizenship is required. An exis
 ting security clearance\, or eligibility to obtain one\, is helpful but no
 t required. DEADLINE: applications are due July 22\, 2026.\n\nOrganisation
 : Horizon Institute for Public Service\nLocation: Washington\, DC area\, U
 nited States (in-person\; full-time placements in U.S. executive branch of
 fices).\nAward: Fellow track: USD 170\,000 to 200\,000+\, plus an addition
 al stipend for benefits. Senior Fellow track: from USD 250\,000+\, plus a 
 benefits stipend\, commensurate with the seniority of the placement.\nDura
 tion: One year full-time\, with the opportunity for renewal.\n\nMore: http
 s://horizonpublicservice.org/ai-rapid-response-fellowship/?utm_source=arti
 ficialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://horizonpublicservice.org/ai-rapid-response-fellowship/?utm_sour
 ce=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Washington\, DC area\, United States (in-person\; full-time placem
 ents in U.S. executive branch offices).
